definition.value: A triglyceride in which the three acyl groups contain a total of 53 carbons and 3 double bonds.
A triglyceride in which the three acyl groups contain a total of 56 carbons and 6 double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 35 carbons in total with 2 double bonds.
A ceramide in which the acyl group and the sphingoid base contain a total of 42 carbon atoms and 1 double bond.
A ceramide in which the acyl group and the sphingoid base contain a total of 42 carbon atoms and 2 double bonds.
A triglyceride in which the three acyl groups contain a total of 51 carbons and 4 double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 33 carbons in total with 2 double bonds.
Any mammalian metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in rat (Rattus norvegicus).
Any antifungal agent used to prevent or treat fungal infections in humans or animals.
Any substance used in acriculture, horticulture, forestry, etc. for its fungicidal properties.
An arginine derivative that is arginine substituted by two methyl groups. A "closed" class.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the acyl groups specified at C-1 and C-2 contain 33 carbons in total with 1 double bond.
A hydroxy-amino acid in which the amino acid specified is proline. A "closed" class.
Any organic aromatic compound containing two phenyl (or substituted phenyl) groups attached to a single carbon or heteroatom and which has been used as a fungicide.
An organonitrogen compound that contains an amino group that is attached to a carbon which is itself attached to an olefinic carbon and which has been used as an antifungal drug.
A class of sulfonamides whose members generally have bacteriostatic antibiotic properties.
A member of the class of furans in which the furan ring is substituted by a nitro group and which also has significant antibiotic properties.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of two of the three diphosphate OH groups of adenosine 5'-diphosphate.

Any organooxygen compound whose structure is related to compactin (mevastatin) and which may be used as an anticholesteremic drug due its EC 1.1.1.34/EC 1.1.1.88 (hydroxymethylglutaryl-CoA reductase) inhibitory properties.

Any statin that occurs in nature. The class includes compactin (also known as mevastatin), isolated from a fermentation broth of Penicillium citrinum, and lovastatin, isolated from Aspergillus terreus.
A statin that is derived from a naturally occurring statin by partial chemical synthesis.
A statin which does not occur naturally and which is not obtained by chemical transformation of a naturally occurring statin.
A member of the class of coumarins that is 4-hydroxycoumarin which is substituted at position 3 by a 1-phenyl-3-oxo-1-butyl group.
A 4-hydroxy-3-(3-oxo-1-phenylbutyl)-2H-1-benzopyran-2-one that has (R)-configuration (the racemate is warfarin, an anticoagulant drug and rodenticide).
A 4-hydroxy-3-(3-oxo-1-phenylbutyl)-2H-1-benzopyran-2-one that has (S)-configuration (the racemate is warfarin, an anticoagulant drug and rodenticide).
An organic anion that is the conjugate base of (R)-warfarin,  obtained by deprotonation of the hydroxy group.
An organic anion that is the conjugate base of (S)-warfarin, obtained by deprotonation of the hydroxy group.
A ketohexose monophosphate consisting of fructose having a phosphate group located at the 6-position.
A phosphoglycerate obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group and one of the phosphate OH groups of 3-phosphoglyceric acid.
Any organic amino compound that contains two or more amino groups.
Any metal which causes the onset of an allergic reaction.
Any drug which causes the onset of an allergic reaction.
A primary ammonium ion obtained by protonation of the amino group of an aralkylamine; major species at pH 7.3.
A phosphoglycerate obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy and phosphate OH groups of 2-phosphoglyceric acid.

A member of the class of pyridopyrimidines that is 2-methyl-6,7,8,9-tetrahydropyrido[1,2-a]pyrimidin-4-one carrying an additional 2-[4-(6-fluoro-1,2-benzoxazol-3-yl)piperidin-1-yl]ethyl group at position 2.

A member of the class of pyranoindolizinoquinolines that is (4S)-pyrano[3',4':6,7]indolizino[1,2-b]quinoline-3,14-dione bearing two additional ethyl substituents at positions 4 and 11 as well as two additional hydroxy substituents at positions 4 and 9. It is the active metabolite of irinotecan and is ~1000 times more active than irinotecan itself.
An EC 6.4.1.* (carboxylase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of pyruvate carboxylase (EC 6.4.1.1).
An icosanoid anion that is the conjugate base of 12(S)-HETE, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A guanidinium ion obtained by monoprotonation of metformin.
A drug that acts as an antagonist, agonist, reverse agonist, or in some other fashion when interacting with cellular receptors.
An icosanoid anion that is the conjugate base of 12-HETE arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function; major species at pH 7.3.
Any peptide zwitterion comprising two amino acid residues. Major structure at pH 7.3.
A hydroxy fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of 13(S)-HODE, arising from deprotonation of the carboxylic acid function; major species at pH 7.3.
A mixed diacylamine resulting from the formal condensation of the nitrogen of a carboxamide with a sulphonic acid.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the tertiary amino group of irinotecan.
A carboxylic acic anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any aromatic carboxylic acid. Major species at pH 7.3.
An antagonist at purinergic P2 receptors
A 2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the 2-acyl group contains 20 carbons and 4 double bonds.
